[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":505},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema\u002F":480,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema\u002F":489},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20220221\u002F3674730635\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":460,"date":461,"description":462,"extension":463,"lang":464,"meta":465,"navigation":466,"path":467,"readingMinutes":468,"seo":469,"standalone":470,"stem":471,"tags":472,"tldr":477,"updated":461,"url":478,"__hash__":479},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema.md","(9) The Frontend Dev Forced to Eat Mango - Mongoose: Connecting to MongoDB and Writing Your First Schema","1003349740",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":455},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,36,39,79,82,102,109,116,127,145,167,242,252,257,267,272,276,279,282,298,309,329,332,368,371,437,448,451],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Next up we're heading into the Express development chapters, which means we'll start using Mongoose to connect to the database. But the very first move, basically, is getting familiar with the Schema.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"connect-mongodb","Connect MongoDB",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35],{},"I'm assuming you've already built an Express app with express-generator. So inside that project, create a folder called ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"connections",", and then a file inside it called ",[28,33,34],{},"database.js",".",[17,37,38],{},"Connecting to MongoDB is pretty simple. First, require Mongoose:",[40,41,46],"pre",{"className":42,"code":43,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const mongoose = require('mongoose');\n","js","",[28,47,48],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,50,53,57,61,64,68,72,76],"span",{"class":51,"line":52},"line",1,[49,54,56],{"class":55},"sWyjQ","const",[49,58,60],{"class":59},"sCcAr"," mongoose",[49,62,63],{"class":55}," =",[49,65,67],{"class":66},"sj_SG"," require",[49,69,71],{"class":70},"sMAXC","(",[49,73,75],{"class":74},"sTRMh","'mongoose'",[49,77,78],{"class":70},");\n",[17,80,81],{},"Then write the connection:",[40,83,85],{"className":42,"code":84,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"mongoose.connect('MongoDB URL');\n",[28,86,87],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,88,89,92,95,97,100],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,90,91],{"class":70},"mongoose.",[49,93,94],{"class":66},"connect",[49,96,71],{"class":70},[49,98,99],{"class":74},"'MongoDB URL'",[49,101,78],{"class":70},[17,103,104,105,108],{},"Where do you get the MongoDB URL? Type ",[28,106,107],{},"mongo"," in your terminal and you'll see it up top:",[17,110,111],{},[112,113],"img",{"alt":114,"src":115},"MongoDB URL","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F202201292205.png",[17,117,118,119,122,123,126],{},"So the URL is ",[28,120,121],{},"mongodb:\u002F\u002F127.0.0.1:27017",". Here we'll also specify which database we want to connect to — say ",[28,124,125],{},"example"," — like this:",[40,128,130],{"className":42,"code":129,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"mongoose.connect('mongodb:\u002F\u002F127.0.0.1:27017\u002Fexample');\n",[28,131,132],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,133,134,136,138,140,143],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,135,91],{"class":70},[49,137,94],{"class":66},[49,139,71],{"class":70},[49,141,142],{"class":74},"'mongodb:\u002F\u002F127.0.0.1:27017\u002Fexample'",[49,144,78],{"class":70},[17,146,147,148,151,152,155,156,159,160,163,164,166],{},"Now you can head back into ",[28,149,150],{},"app.js"," and just write ",[28,153,154],{},"require('.\u002Fconnections\u002Fdatabase');",". When you run ",[28,157,158],{},"npm start"," in the terminal, you'll notice there's no message at all — because by default, ",[28,161,162],{},"mongoose"," won't tell you it connected. So open up ",[28,165,34],{}," again and add these two lines:",[40,168,170],{"className":42,"code":169,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"mongoose.connection.once('open', () => console.log('connected to database'));\nmongoose.connection.on('error', (error) => console.error('database error', error));\n",[28,171,172,205],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,173,174,177,180,182,185,188,191,194,197,199,202],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,175,176],{"class":70},"mongoose.connection.",[49,178,179],{"class":66},"once",[49,181,71],{"class":70},[49,183,184],{"class":74},"'open'",[49,186,187],{"class":70},", () ",[49,189,190],{"class":55},"=>",[49,192,193],{"class":70}," console.",[49,195,196],{"class":66},"log",[49,198,71],{"class":70},[49,200,201],{"class":74},"'connected to database'",[49,203,204],{"class":70},"));\n",[49,206,208,210,213,215,218,221,225,228,230,232,234,236,239],{"class":51,"line":207},2,[49,209,176],{"class":70},[49,211,212],{"class":66},"on",[49,214,71],{"class":70},[49,216,217],{"class":74},"'error'",[49,219,220],{"class":70},", (",[49,222,224],{"class":223},"s_sBn","error",[49,226,227],{"class":70},") ",[49,229,190],{"class":55},[49,231,193],{"class":70},[49,233,224],{"class":66},[49,235,71],{"class":70},[49,237,238],{"class":74},"'database error'",[49,240,241],{"class":70},", error));\n",[17,243,244,245,247,248,251],{},"The first line uses ",[28,246,179],{},", which means \"only fire this one time.\" Once you're connected to the database, it outputs ",[28,249,250],{},"connected to database",":",[17,253,254],{},[112,255],{"alt":250,"src":256},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-29%2022.16.54.png",[17,258,259,260,262,263,266],{},"The second line uses ",[28,261,212],{},", which listens for error messages in real time. So if MongoDB suddenly can't connect, ",[28,264,265],{},"database error"," pops out immediately:",[17,268,269],{},[112,270],{"alt":265,"src":271},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-01-29%2022.33.16.png",[12,273,275],{"id":274},"schema","Schema",[17,277,278],{},"A Schema is basically the \"structure\" of your data. We've already connected to MongoDB through Mongoose, so the next step is to define a Schema — which is kind of similar to the Model concept.",[17,280,281],{},"The Schema is like telling MongoDB what kind of data we want to store. So first, let's define a user table. When a user signs up, what data do they usually have to provide? The common ones are:",[283,284,285,289,292,295],"ul",{},[286,287,288],"li",{},"User account",[286,290,291],{},"User password",[286,293,294],{},"User nickname",[286,296,297],{},"Account creation date",[17,299,300,301,304,305,308],{},"How do we write that? First, create a ",[28,302,303],{},"Model"," folder under your project, name the file ",[28,306,307],{},"User.js",", then require Mongoose inside it:",[40,310,311],{"className":42,"code":43,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},[28,312,313],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,314,315,317,319,321,323,325,327],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,316,56],{"class":55},[49,318,60],{"class":59},[49,320,63],{"class":55},[49,322,67],{"class":66},[49,324,71],{"class":70},[49,326,75],{"class":74},[49,328,78],{"class":70},[17,330,331],{},"Once that's done, declare a variable to hold the Schema instance:",[40,333,335],{"className":42,"code":334,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({\n  ...\n});\n",[28,336,337,357,362],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,338,339,341,344,346,349,352,354],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,340,56],{"class":55},[49,342,343],{"class":59}," UserSchema",[49,345,63],{"class":55},[49,347,348],{"class":55}," new",[49,350,351],{"class":70}," mongoose.",[49,353,275],{"class":66},[49,355,356],{"class":70},"({\n",[49,358,359],{"class":51,"line":207},[49,360,361],{"class":55},"  ...\n",[49,363,365],{"class":51,"line":364},3,[49,366,367],{"class":70},"});\n",[17,369,370],{},"The contents are dead simple — just fill in the object properties one by one. If you've written Vue before, you might find it feels a lot like the Props concept. Here I'll just drop in the relevant fields:",[40,372,374],{"className":42,"code":373,"language":44,"meta":45,"style":45},"const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({\n  account: String,\n  password: String,\n  nickname: String,\n  createTime: {\n    type: Date,\n    default: Date.now,\n  }\n});\n",[28,375,376,392,397,402,408,414,420,426,432],{"__ignoreMap":45},[49,377,378,380,382,384,386,388,390],{"class":51,"line":52},[49,379,56],{"class":55},[49,381,343],{"class":59},[49,383,63],{"class":55},[49,385,348],{"class":55},[49,387,351],{"class":70},[49,389,275],{"class":66},[49,391,356],{"class":70},[49,393,394],{"class":51,"line":207},[49,395,396],{"class":70},"  account: String,\n",[49,398,399],{"class":51,"line":364},[49,400,401],{"class":70},"  password: String,\n",[49,403,405],{"class":51,"line":404},4,[49,406,407],{"class":70},"  nickname: String,\n",[49,409,411],{"class":51,"line":410},5,[49,412,413],{"class":70},"  createTime: {\n",[49,415,417],{"class":51,"line":416},6,[49,418,419],{"class":70},"    type: Date,\n",[49,421,423],{"class":51,"line":422},7,[49,424,425],{"class":70},"    default: Date.now,\n",[49,427,429],{"class":51,"line":428},8,[49,430,431],{"class":70},"  }\n",[49,433,435],{"class":51,"line":434},9,[49,436,367],{"class":70},[17,438,439,440,443,444,447],{},"You'll notice ",[28,441,442],{},"createTime"," has a special ",[28,445,446],{},"default"," written for it. The reason is that when a user creates their account, the creation date should be filled in automatically, so the user doesn't have to provide it.",[17,449,450],{},"And that's the simplest, most basic way to write a Schema. In the next post, I'll start digging into the details of what goes inside a Schema.",[452,453,454],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}",{"title":45,"searchDepth":207,"depth":207,"links":456},[457,458,459],{"id":14,"depth":207,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":207,"text":23},{"id":274,"depth":207,"text":275},"Nodejs","2022-02-21 09:00:19","Next up we're heading into the Express development chapters, which means we'll start using Mongoose to connect to the database. But the very first thing you need to get familiar with is the Schema. In this post I'll walk through connecting to MongoDB with Mongoose and defining your first user Schema.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema","3",{"title":6,"description":462},false,"en\u002FNodejs\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-schema",[473,474,475,275,476],"MongoDB","Mongoose","Node.js","The Frontend Dev Forced to Eat Mango",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F02\u002F21\u002Fforced-to-eat-mango-09-mongoose-connect-mongodb-sc